Went in today to Stone age farmacy just to browse checked in at the main entrance with the  young lady at the front reception desk.quickly my girlfriend and I got the ok to go to the back got my ftp deal it was nice.went inside to the back and was greeted by the bud tender JoJo which by far she did a wonderful job taking care of my girlfriend and me.we asked to see the cartridges, she recommended the California Dab Company cartridges to my girlfriend and i.(full gram each) bought one got the Trainwreck   strain and omg ...... I do not remember the date to be exact but it was in December I believe...I am new to this legal weed thing so I really do not know how to buy weed. I did not get what I wanted because she was not listening to a thing I said. Then she asked me my name, I said, "Abraham". Upon checking me out, my daughter called my phone with an emergency, so unaware of what I was doing because it was my daughter calling; I answered the call. The manager (a black guy) told me that I needed to get off my phone. I blew my breath at what my daughter was saying because of what she said to me on the phone. <review>Nice, large & clean all around place, with very helpful, patient staff, who'll gladly take you through everything that they have in stock, item by item if need be, as well as any "specials"(of which I understand there are quite a few, & are "on" daily, including a "NEW patient/customer", on your very 1st visit) which'll  be "on" for that day.

They carry a pretty decent-size selection of just about everything you might want: from reg. buds, oils, hash, edibles, to plants, & even sell pre-rolled single smokes (starting from $5/ea & up, depending on quality, of course. & I must say that the $5 "house blend" that I've tried was pretty darn good in taste, smell, & more importantly potency). You can even get 'em in a pack, like reg. cigarettes.
Everything that I've tried here, so far, has been of GOOD quality, with pretty reasonable prices.

You WILL get a BETTER price IF you HAVE a Dr's recommendation (due to the HUMONGOUS, 34.5% "CA Cannabis TAX" on all meds sold for the RECREATIONAL use, but that's not their doing/fault, & is likely the same everywhere else in CA?!), PARTICULARLY on their "specials", as well as "in the long run", via having to pay FAR less in taxes.

HOWEVER(!) you *DO NOT NEED a DR. recommendation (*as long as you're NOT at the LONG BEACH branch, for now), you ONLY NEED YOUR VALID CA ID/DL to get in/make a purchase. There is a private parking area upfront, it's EASILY visible off the street, & is RIGHT off the 110 FWY.< /review><rating>5< /rating>< user>

< Review>
None of these reviews are actually for the museum (they are for the campground). The museum is AWESOME.  It has limited hours, but if you can make the 3.1+ mile 1,300 foot uphill hike it's worth it!! 5< /rate>
< text>
Excellent workout. Straight up the fire service road for about 3 miles. Best to go early before the sun comes out strong since the road is fully exposed and has very little shade. Take plenty of water because it is not available once you get there. Keep in mind a 90 degree will sap your energy and hydration is a must. It takes about an hour to get up to Henninger Flats give or take a few minutes.< /text>

<text>Being on the lower end, just inside the Angeles Forest, you'll never be fully secluded here. These trails are very populated & on top on that very well maintained. Feeling the air shift cooler as you curve up, dipping into the pocket of the mountain.</text></record>

< userid>
102358566443682745574</userid>
< user_name>
Bradley Martin</user_name>
<time>1574362591630< /time><rating>5<//rating>< text>
It's a great place to hike to from Eaton Canyon... If you're NEW pay attention! There is a "contributor" Tatiana Lopez that appears to have uploaded 2500+ photos and tagged them as being taken at Henninger Flats. They are NOT properly tagged... and I've exhausted reported as many as I can... but it will take forever! So just ignore her photos... there is a very obvious difference in her photos verses what others have posted/tagged.

For those Hiking up from Eaton Canyon... it is a challenging elevation climb, but an easy hike as the trail is quite clear and wide. The trail is the "fire road" that leads up to Henninger (which was repaired a number of years ago after a landslide took out large portions of the road (and mountain side)... I'm glad it was reopened... and for those wanting a big challenge you can continue up to Mt. Wilson if you're feeling bold!

Remember to "leave no trace" and keep your 10 essentials with you. This is still wild country with spiders, snakes, bears and mountain lions in the area. So please, don't treat your hike as if you're going to Tom Sawyer Island and Disneyland. You can get hurt if you're not being safe. People have fallen from ledges and been hurt (a few killed) so treat nature with respect and stay firmly on the trails.

YIS,
-Bradley</text>

<pics>None<//pics><Resp>None< /Resp>< text>
It's a great place to hike to from Eaton Canyon... If you're NEW pay attention! There is a "contributor" Tatiana Lopez that appears to have uploaded 2500+ photos and tagged them as being taken at Henninger Flats. They are NOT properly tagged... and I've exhausted reported as many as I can... but it will take forever! So just ignore her photos... there is a very obvious difference in her photos verses what others have posted/tagged.

For those Hiking up from Eaton Canyon... it is a challenging elevation climb, but an easy hike as the trail is quite clear and wide. The trail is the "fire road" that leads up to Henninger (which was repaired a number of years ago after a landslide took out large portions of the road (and mountain side)... I'm glad it was reopened... and for those wanting a big challenge you can continue up to Mt. Wilson if you're feeling bold!

Remember to "leave no trace" and keep your 10 essentials with you. This is still wild country with spiders, snakes, bears and mountain lions in the area. So please, don't treat your hike as if you're going to Tom Sawyer Island and Disneyland. You can get hurt if you're not being safe. People have fallen from ledges and been hurt (a few killed) so treat nature with respect and stay firmly on the trails.

YIS,
-Bradley< /text>

0x80c2dd2201383f4b:0x21496be732eb4eb3< /gmap_id>
<response>None</response><user_name>Joshua & Darby<//user_name><Date>1619713513137< /Date><text>In May I made the move from Seattle to Los Angeles and it didn‚Äôt take long for me to start itching to get outdoors and explore. Unfortunately it took me a couple weeks to settle in and finally make time to get out. I started doing some research on recommended places to camp near LA and Henniger Flats was at the top of almost everyone‚Äôs list that I could find online. A short hike, free camping and not far from where I live; sold. Especially for my first camping adventure since making the move to sunny California.

Henniger Flats is located in the San Gabriel Mountains near Altadena, California. Directions on getting there are pretty simple coming from downtown LA.

The trailhead to Henniger Flats is located off N Altadena Drive. It‚Äôs not easy to spot but if you‚Äôre familiar with the area, you‚Äôll probably have no problem finding it. If you‚Äôre heading to Henniger Flats for the night, you‚Äôll have to pay attention to where you park because there‚Äôs not a lot of overnight or long-term parking at the trailhead. I personally parked down the street on N Altadena in the neighborhood. Just keep an eye out for parking signs and you‚Äôll probably be ok.

When you reach the trailhead you‚Äôll see a sign that reads, ‚ÄúThe Henniger Flats Project.‚Äù You have to hike up  Mount Wilson Toll Road to get there. Initially it‚Äôs a little confusing to figure out which trail you need to be on to get there, at least it was for me. You‚Äôll walk down the beginning of the trail and cross the white bridge. Once you cross the white bridge, stay to the left and head up until you reach Henniger Flats. It‚Äôs about a 3 mile hike and the incline gets steep at times. There are plenty of benches to rest at on the way up.

There‚Äôs no shade on the way up so it‚Äôs important to start your hike early if you intend on camping and have a heavy pack. Also bring an abundance of water. There is a visitor center and museum at Henniger Flats, but there‚Äôs no running water. Be prepared! I didn‚Äôt run into any wildlife and you probably won‚Äôt either since the trail is very popular and there seems to be a lot of foot traffic throughout the day. There are a few signs for rattlesnakes but I didn‚Äôt run into any.

After your 3 mile journey to the top, you‚Äôve reached Henniger Flats. First thing‚Äôs first, you need to find the onsite LACFD Forester that‚Äôs on duty to check in. I read that you‚Äôll be given a permit for camping and to use a stove, but I didn‚Äôt have to do that when I checked in for whatever reason. There was a cub scout clan doing some work at the campgrounds so I‚Äôm sure he was busy and distracted. After or even before you check in, you can check out the visitor center and museum to learn about Henniger Flats and the surrounding areas. It‚Äôs pretty neat.

Once you get checked in you‚Äôll have to find your camping lot. There are 3 levels of camping at Henniger Flats. There‚Äôs a lower level campground near the visitor center and museum. It seemed pretty busy, so I walked to the upper and Fiji campgrounds. The forester actually recommended the Fiji campground area for a quieter environment and great place for setting up hammocks. He was absolutely right and if you‚Äôre looking for a quiet place to chillax, Fiji is the way to go.

Most larger camping lots have picnic tables and stoves to cook on. It‚Äôs worth noting there are about 15-20 camping lots in the upper and lower campgrounds. Fiji only has 3 camping lots, so you have to get there early to snag one. You can also call the forester head of time to get some insight on open camp lots. There‚Äôs plenty of shade once you get settled and the campgrounds are very well kept. There was no trash, the trails were well maintained and the views are phenomenal. There‚Äôs plenty of trails to check out after you get settled in.

Overall I had a great experience camping at Henniger Flats and I will certainly go again. #LosAngeles #Hiking #Outdoors<//text><UserId.>106154296122714978938< /UserId.></record></dataset><record>
<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
Went camping at the campground. It's a few miles to hike up to and you have to carry everything in and out. The hike is not too hard but if you are carrying equipment then it quickly becomes a strenuous hike. The campground is beautiful and offers a fabulous view of LA. They have grills to cook in and make fires inside. No fires allowed outside of the grills. Free firewood is also available but water is not currently running.< /text>

<user_name>Ark M (Mushedroom's Toy Box)<//user_name>< Text>
This is an awesome reward for a steep slanted hike/walk up above the Eaton canyon wash. With breath taking views and a campground, you can't help but just take it all in. There are various benches posted at all of the best Vista spots on your way up in case you need a breather or to get pebbles out of your shoes. It is an all packed dirt hike-walk so be sure to have some grippy shoes on. also at the top, there are restrooms and an old timey outhouse. Plus a museum with actual watch towers and other vintage items to check out. We also saw some HUGE silver squirrels!</Text>

116575091785953145580<//userid>
<username>Poodlepassion</username><Date>1536512135291<//Date><rating>5< /rating>< Text>
What a gem of a tack shop!  Marisa (sp?) was super friendly and unexpectedly helpful, going out of her way several times to find answers to my questions about a dressage saddle for my and my horses' needs.  I asked her if she knew of a very specialized feed for my horse.  She didn't know, but she texted a friend of hers, and found the answer I was looking for, that feed store in my area (high desert) could ever answer, or ever take such time to help me.  I really expected some snooty salespeople since they're in such a high-end town, but Marisa was so down-to-earth, she really made me feel comfortable.  My heart sank when I saw a dressage saddle go out the door on trial.  She offered to call me if the people didn't want it, but I live so far away and can't travel back down there to get it.  My loss.  Their used saddles, by the way, are surprisingly very low priced, and they are super quality names.  They have lots in their consignment/used section, and I found the exact bit that I was looking for at a cheap price!  I wish I lived closer, or I'd be quite the regular customer in that place!  Valerie.<//Text>

< text>
Just goes to show you.. you should read reviews before doing business with anyone these days!  It seems that I have fallen victim to the super secret, (made up) return/exchange policy at 5.11 as well? A few days ago I bought 3 pair of pants as well as various other items.  The next day, I pulled the tags off and was going to put a pair of pants on.  It was then that I realized that they were a bit bigger in the waist than I realized in the store.  So I put the tags in the pocket and took them back to the store with the receipt.  I just wanted to exchange for a smaller size, then make an additional purchase that would have amounted to about $1000.00.  2 pairs of 300.00 boots and a half dozen shirts.  The sales person (who was my original salesperson days before)   Explained to me that if the tags have been removed, the store policy was no refunds / no exchanges. I pointed out on my receipt that is not the policy stated in writing?  He said no... it's not in writing it's just a store policy? Then  I begin to argue with him and explained that that's the most ridiculous thing I've ever heard of in my life, we go back-and-forth.  Then he changes his mind about the unwritten policy and he says to me "would you settle for two out of three? I said two out of three what? He said well I can let you exchange two pairs but the third pair has been washed and we can't exchange those. I said to him that they never went more than 3 feet from the bag they've not been washed and they were exactly in the condition which I bought them.  He argued back-and-forth with me again and told me I could call customer service. So I called customer service while standing in the store the phone rang and rang finally somebody answered I explained the problem.. they put me on hold for several minutes came back and said that there was nobody there that could help me and there's nothing they could do for me at that time? What?  So much for customer service I guess? They suggested that I talk to the store manager.   So I hung up the phone and asked the salesperson who is the store manager?    He replied Kristy.   I said fine when would she be back in the store so that I could talk to her about this transaction? I swear I am not making this up...the sales guy said that he's not allowed to tell customers when the manager is going to be in the store it's against store policy. I swear to God I thought I was on an episode of the twilight zone! I said so what do I do?  Do I just call every 20 minutes day after day until she answers the phone to figure out when she's there?  He just said I guess so?  What the???  I will say it's a pretty cool store and they have some pretty cool items.    I am just completely baffled by the way they do business. So, in the end, I asked for a complete refund on the two pairs of pants he didn't argue about, and I told him I would just throw the third pair in the trash and that I would never be back,  I don't think he really cared?   Needless to say, they didn't get it the other thousand dollar sale for me tonight night either?   Way too much work to do business with these guys... it feels like they just make it up as they go? They are great when taking your money... but God help you if you need a little service after the sale.  Ridiculous.  Buyers beware!!!

Just remembered this as well...  while I was in the store for the original purchase, the salesperson told me that the sizes can vary for any two pairs of the same pants.  I was told that it was due to the fact that they are made in two different factories in China.. and they have very little control over the output?  You can tell because the labels inside the pants are different?  The pants are $69.00?  Maybe for that price they should make them in the USA?  Just a thought.< /text>

<user_name>Alyssamarie Smith< /user_name><Date>1476850582023<//Date><rating>5</rating><review>5.11 Store. Ah. The store for military, law enforcement, fire, EMS, and people that like to spend $70+ to dress up and look like they're doing something tactical. Haha. All jokes aside, I'm extremely glad that they have an actual 5.11 store in Sacramento. My go to 5.11 establishment before didn't have a wide variety of womens apparel, but lo and behold when this baby opened up I was in heaven!! They have about 5-6 different womens pants with all of the sizes, polos, gun range gear, belts, shirts, tanks, you name it! They do not skimp on ladies products.

Oh... and for the guys, they have pretty much have all the supplies off the website for you. Hats, patches, pants, polos, etc...

They also have write in the rain supplies, knives, ANSI certified sunglasses, med bag gear stuff, molle gear stuff, belts, shoes and hydroflasks.

Anyway, if you love tactical stuff. You'll be in heaven. Go here, you won't regret it. Also if you love a good sale, go all the way in the back by the shoes. Sometimes they have it up in the front by the women's gear. You're welcome. :)</review>< Pics>

<rating>1< /rating>< text>
I experienced the rudest and uncompassionate grooming appointment.  I have two dogs who have been groomed at various PetSmart throughout their lives (12 and 13 years old) and never had an experience like this.  My older dog accidentally slipped through the backyard gate last night and was taken to the shelter by a kind stranger this morning.  I called the grooming salon immediately to schedule an appointment so my dog can get cleaned.  One Petsmart grooming associate informed me there were 3 appointments available throughout the day.  I scheduled an appointment, but because it took the vet longer than expected to check my dog, I called back to reschedule for a later appointment.  The next associate, Richard, kept finding excuses to cancel the appointment.  After I told him I was aware of an opening later that afternoon, he reluctantly agreed.  Once I arrived (toddler in tow), my poor dog had an accident.  She is nervous at baseline, but given what happened last night, her anxiety was heightened.  I was instructed to walk her around for 15 minutes in the parking lot.  When I explained it was dangerous because I had my 2 year old and cannot manage walking both of them in a crowded parking lot, I was asked to wait in the grooming salon for 15 minutes.  Meanwhile, Richard who never addressed me personally continued to made snide remarks on cancelling my appointment to his associate as if I was not sitting right there. My dog again had an accident. The associate recommended that I go to another grooming salon. Then Richard had two other Petsmart employees come in to tell me that it is their policy to cancel my appointment if a dog has 2 accidents.  They did not ask me any questions and clearly had their mind made up.  Instead of having compassion for the situation, it just felt humiliating.  Not only did I have paperwork from the vet showing that my dog was in good health (examined that morning), but now I wasted an entire day trying to work around this appointment with a young toddler and a traumatized dog.  It was a huge waste of time and energy- just to be treated so rudely.  I was able to make arrangement with a local groomer for tomorrow, but this forced us to change our Mother's Day plans completely.  Very disappointing and will not be returning!<//text>

<UserId.>111644673136196029337<//UserId.><Name>Cary Brown</Name><Date>1528251553839</Date><rating>4< /rating>< text>
PetSmart is a large pet supply store with caring, knowledgeable employees. Jeremy, the assistant store manager, spent over an hour helping my wife and myself select and fit a harness, collar and leash for our dog.

‚úìCats and dogs, available for adoption, are given prominent, air-conditioned space at the front of the store. It gets hot in Encino. Small live animals and fish are available for sale.

So you adopt a companion.  One you can pick up in one hand. Really cute. After a week, your arm feels two inches longer and the tug boat you've adopted is trying to eat the couch. You need help my friend, you and your companion need a trainer. So, you ask a few friends and get recommends for a trainer who cost about as much as your mortgage.  Obviously, you and your buddy need group therapy.

‚úìThat's what PetSmart offers at a reasonable price.  Five Lessons currently cost a litte over one hundred dollars (us). Cookie, our dog friend, loves her trainer, Jasmin. She is kind, and caring. After five classes, she has learned to sit, lay down, come when called, and to walk without pulling. My arm has return to normal.

‚úìPetSart also offers pet grooming at reasonable prices.

‚úìNew owners of adopted pets are presented a coupon booklet offering significant discounts. Proof of adoption is required.  Free parking. Everything is wheelchair accessible.

Several restaurants in the shopping complex offer outdoor seating so you and your companion can enjoy some time together.<//text>

< text>
I love this place. Super cute inside. Great hang out spot. They have board games & books. Power outlets so you can connect charger/laptop. Decorative wall to takes pictures.

Love the Matcha Green tea. This time had it with crystal boba, pretty good. I'm not into regular boba. The peeps are super chill & friendly. Have extended menu and very inexpensive. They have Vegan options.
